          <avActivityHighlights>As a consequence of new snow a moderate danger of dry and wet avalanches will prevail.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Up to 20 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, fell on Tuesday above approximately 1600 m. &lt;br/&gt; In particular in the regions exposed to heavier precipitation and on very steep slopes small and, in isolated cases, medium-sized dry and wet avalanches are possible. They can in isolated cases be released, even by a single winter sport participant. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Restraint should be exercised because avalanches can sweep people along and give rise to falls.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Over a wide area 15 to 20 cm of snow, and up to 30 cm in some localities, fell on Tuesday above approximately 1600 m. &lt;br/&gt; The new snow is lying on a crust and generally at low and intermediate altitudes. The new snow is lying on surface hoar in some places on shady slopes at high altitude. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; High Alpine regions: Weak layers exist in the snowpack especially on shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Over a wide area there is still a very large amount of snow.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
